text: gaining more and more appreciation for {lubridate} as i work more with date time data #RStats https://t.co/DnLnRHs6mT

@Ade2unge @rstats_tweets between doesn't work with datetime, but {lubridate} can help #RStats

library(lubridate)
set.seed(1)

last_month <- ymd(20211015) - 0:29

df <- tibble::tibble(
  date = last_month,
  price = runif(30)
)

dplyr::filter(df, date %within% interval(ymd(20210925), ymd(20211005)))

a small developer experience improvement, but really nice that there's an #RStats dplyr::between() function so I can do

filter(starwars, between(height, 100, 150))

instead of 

filter(starwars, height >= 100 & height <= 150)

🙌

@overmanra @minigamedev dplyr::select(df, 2, everything ()) 

will remove the column with index 2 from whole list of columns and move it to FIRST position.

You could use column name as well.

Eg.

dplyr::select(iris, Sepal.Width, everything ())

#dplyr #RStats
(3/3)

@overmanra @minigamedev dplyr::select(df, -1, everything ()) 

will remove the column with index 1 from list of columns and move it to last.

You could use column name as well.

Eg.

dplyr::select(iris, -Sepal.Length, everything ())

#dplyr #RStats
(1/3)

@overmanra @minigamedev Negative index AFTER everything () will do what usually negative index does... Removes it from list.
Positive index AFTER everything () will not duplicate column.
dplyr:: select (iris, everything (), -1) or 
dplyr::select(iris, everything (), -Sepal.Length)
#RStats (2/3)

mutate(n =n()) %>%
